Osteochondrosis is a type of bone disease that occurs when the blood supply to a part of the bone is reduced, leading to necrosis (death) of the bone tissue. It most commonly affects children and teenagers who are still growing and developing. Osteochondrosis can cause pain, swelling, and limited mobility in the affected joint. In some cases, it may also result in a popping or cracking sound when the affected joint is moved. Treatment options for osteochondrosis include rest, ice, compression, elevation, and medications to help manage pain and reduce inflammation. Surgery is generally only required in severe cases where the bone has broken apart or is significantly damaged.

Septic arthritis, also known as infectious arthritis, is a type of arthritis that occurs due to an infection in the joint. It can cause symptoms such as pain, swelling, and stiffness in the affected joint. Septic arthritis is usually caused by bacteria, but it can also be caused by viruses or fungi. It's important to seek medical attention if you experience these symptoms, as septic arthritis requires treatment with antibiotics and other medications to address the infection and prevent further joint damage.

Columnar cell breast carcinoma is a type of breast mucinous carcinoma. Columnar cell breast carcinoma has the definition of a breast mucinous carcinoma that is characterized by tall columnar cells with basal, bland nuclei, intracytoplasmic and extracytoplasmic mucin and is grossly solid. It also has an exact synonym of Columnar Cell Change of the Breast and blunt duct adenosis of breast.

Epiglottis cancer, also known as malignant tumor of the Epiglottis, is a type of supraglottis cancer that occurs when abnormal cells grow and divide uncontrollably in the epiglottis region of the throat. The exact synonym for this condition is "epiglottic cancer." It is important to note that the epiglottis is the flap-like structure located at the base of the tongue, which prevents dust and food particles from entering the windpipe during swallowing. When cancer develops in this area, it can make swallowing difficult and cause other complications. Early detection and proper treatment are crucial to increase the chances of successful recovery.

Gallbladder lymphoma is a type of cancer that originates in the lymphatic system, and specifically affects the gallbladder. The term "gallbladder lymphoma" refers to malignant lymphoid cells that have invaded the gallbladder from surrounding lymph nodes or other parts of the body. It is not a separate type of cancer from lymphoma in general, but rather a specific subtype of the disease that affects the gallbladder.
It's worth noting that there are different subtypes of lymphoma, and the specific type of lymphoma that affects the gallbladder is called "Lymphoma of the Gallbladder".

Correct, thymus clear cell carcinoma, also known as clear cell carcinoma of the Thymus, is a type of cancer that originates in the thymus gland. The thymus is an organ located in the chest, just behind the sternum and in front of the heart. It plays a crucial role in the immune system by producing T cells, which are important for fighting off infections and diseases.

Thymic carcinoma, including clear cell carcinoma, is a rare type of cancer that accounts for less than 5% of all thymus gland tumors. It typically occurs in adults and may present with symptoms such as chest pain, difficulty swallowing, cough, or fatigue. Diagnosis often involves a combination of imaging tests like CT scans, MRI, and biopsy to determine the exact type of cancer.

Treatment for thymic carcinoma depends on the stage and location of the tumor, but it generally includes surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these treatments. It's important to note that each case is unique, and the most appropriate treatment plan will be determined by a healthcare professional based on individual circumstances.

Thymic carcinosarcoma, also known as thymus sarcomatoid carcinoma, is a type of cancer that arises from the thymus gland. The thymus is located in the chest and plays an important role in the development of the immune system. Thymic carcinosarcoma can occur in both children and adults, but it is more common in children.

This type of cancer is characterized by a mixture of malignant thymus tissue and sarcoma, which are soft, spongy tumors made up of connective tissue. Thymic carcinosarcoma can be difficult to diagnose because the symptoms can be similar to other conditions, such as asthma or bronchitis.

Treatment for thymic carcinosarcoma typically involves a combination of surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy. The prognosis for this type of cancer is generally poor, with a five-year survival rate of less than 10 percent. However, advancements in treatment and improved understanding of the disease are leading to better outcomes for some patients.

It's important to note that thymic carcinosarcoma is rare, accounting for only about 5% of all thymus tumors. If you have any concerns or questions about this condition, it's best to consult with a healthcare professional.

Chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) and small lymphocytic lymphoma (SLL) are types of cancer that affect the white blood cells, specifically the lymphocytes. CLL is a slow-growing type of leukemia that affects the production of blood cells in the bone marrow and can lead to anemia or an increased risk of infections. SLL is a type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that affects the small lymphocytes, which are a type of white blood cell found throughout the body. It can cause swelling in the lymph nodes, spleen and liver.
It's worth noting that there is a subtype of CLL called Germinal Center B-Cell Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma (GCB) that has been renamed to Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia/Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma (CLL/SLL) with Unmutated IGVH. This subtype is characterized by the presence of a specific gene mutation called IGVH, which is associated with a more aggressive form of the disease.

Malignant childhood germ cell neoplasm is a type of cancer that originates in the germ cells during childhood. The term "germ cell" refers to the reproductive cells that give rise to sperm and eggs. This type of cancer can occur in both boys and girls, although it is more common in males. It can affect various parts of the body, including the ovaries, testes, and brain. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, back pain, and swelling or a mass in the affected area. Treatment usually involves surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy, depending on the stage and location of the cancer. Prognosis varies based on factors such as age, tumor type, and overall health.

appendiceal L-cell glucagon-like peptide producing tumor is a type of appendix cancer.
appendiceal L-cell glucagon-like peptide producing tumor has exact synonym malignant appendiceal L-cell glucagon-like peptide producing tumour.

That is correct. Fibroosseous pseudotumor of digits, also known as fibroosseous digital pseudotumor, is a type of bone benign neoplasm that affects the fingers and toes. It occurs when there is excessive growth of fibrous tissue around the joints, leading to swelling and deformity. The exact cause of this condition is not known, but it can be triggered by trauma or repetitive stress injuries. Treatment typically involves surgical removal of the affected bone and surrounding tissues, as well as physical therapy to help restore function and prevent future complications.

C5 Deficiency: An Inherited Immune System Disorder
======================================================

C5 deficiency, also known as complement component 5 (C5) deficiency, is an inherited immune system disorder characterized by a susceptibility to recurrent bacterial infections, particularly those involving enveloped organisms. This condition is caused by a mutation in the C5 gene on chromosome 9q33.2, which encodes the fifth component of the complement system. The complement system is an essential part of the innate immune system and plays a crucial role in protecting the body against infections.

Symptoms of C5 Deficiency
-------------------------

Individuals with C5 deficiency are more prone to bacterial infections, particularly those caused by enveloped organisms such as Neisseria meningitidis and Streptococcus pneumoniae. The severity of symptoms can vary greatly among affected individuals, ranging from mild illnesses to life-threatening infections. Some common symptoms include fever, headache, stiff neck, and a stiff back, which are collectively known as meningitis.

Diagnosis of C5 Deficiency
---------------------------

C5 deficiency can be diagnosed through genetic testing, which identifies mutations in the C5 gene. A positive result indicates that an individual has a functional deficiency in complement component 5, increasing their susceptibility to bacterial infections. Treatment of C5 Deficiency
-------------------------------

There is no cure for C5 deficiency, and treatment primarily focuses on managing symptoms and preventing infections. Individuals with this condition should receive regular monitoring by a healthcare professional to ensure timely treatment of any potential infections. Additionally, vaccinations are recommended to protect against common bacterial pathogens, such as pneumococcus and meningococcus.

Living With C5 Deficiency
---------------------------

While there is no cure for C5 deficiency, individuals with this condition can still lead full and productive lives if proper precautions are taken to manage their symptoms and prevent infections. With the support of healthcare professionals and adherence to recommended guidelines, those affected can minimize the risks associated with recurrent bacterial infections and maintain a high quality of life.

Conclusion
----------

C5 deficiency is an inherited immune system disorder that increases susceptibility to bacterial infections, particularly those involving enveloped organisms. With proper diagnosis, management, and adherence to recommended guidelines, individuals with C5 deficiency can lead fulfilling lives despite the increased risk of infections.

Thyroid gland Hurthle cell carcinoma is a specific type of thyroid cancer that features large cells with eosinophilic granular cytoplasm and pleomorphic nuclei. It's also known as Oncocytic carcinoma of the thyroid.

Thyroid Hurthle Cell Adenoma is a type of follicular adenoma that affects the thyroid gland. It is characterized by the presence of Hurthle cells, which are specialized cells found within the thyroid tissue. This condition is also known as benign oncocytoma of the thyroid.

Gallbladder melanoma, also known as malignant melanoma of the gallbladder, is a rare and aggressive type of cancer that originates in the pigment-producing cells called melanocytes. It can affect both the outer (epidermal) and inner (dermal) layers of the skin or other organs and tissues such as the gallbladder, liver, spleen, and gastrointestinal tract. The incidence of gallbladder melanoma is very low compared to other types of melanoma, which typically arise on sun-exposed areas of the skin. However, it is important to note that exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation can increase the risk of developing melanoma, including gallbladder melanoma. Symptoms may include abdominal pain or discomfort, jaundice, nausea, and vomiting. If you have concerns about gallbladder melanoma or any other type of melanoma, it is important to speak with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Fibroepithelial polyp of the anus is a benign (non-cancerous) growth that occurs in the anal canal. It is also known as a fibroid polyps of the anus or a skin tag of the anus. These growths are typically small, ranging from 1 to 2 centimeters in size, and can be found on either side of the anal opening. They are usually painless and do not cause any significant symptoms. However, they may become irritated if they grow larger or come into contact with clothing or other objects. Fibroepithelial polyps of the anus are typically diagnosed through a colonoscopy, sigmoidoscopy, or proctoscopy. They can be removed by a doctor during a routine examination or through a separate procedure.

Endocervical type cervical adenomyoma is a specific subtype of cervical adenomyoma, which refers to a benign tumor consisting of glandular tissue found in the endocervix. This particular subtype is characterized by its location within the endocervical canal and the presence of irregularly shaped, benign glands, as well as smooth muscle.

endometrial type cervical adenomyoma is a specific type of cervical adenomyoma, characterized by glands and cysts lined with a single layer of endocervical-type mucinous epithelium admixed with smooth muscle.

Cervical atypical polypoid adenomyoma is a type of cervical adenomyoma that has the definition as a cervical adenomyoma which is a tumor of endometrium, lower uterine segment and endocervix. It is characterized by atypical complex glands with squamous metaplasia mixed with myofibromatous stroma.

Fallopian tube gestational choriocarcinoma is a specific type of gestational choriocarcinoma that occurs in the fallopian tube. It has the same definition as Gestational Choriocarcinoma of the Fallopian Tube, which is a gestational choriocarcinoma located in the fallopian tube.

Gestational choriocarcinoma, also known as placental-site trophoblastic neoplasia, is a type of cancer that arises from the tissue that forms the placenta during pregnancy. It can be classified into three main subtypes based on its location and appearance under the microscope:

1. Placental site trophoblastic neoplasia (PSTN): This subtype is located in or around the placenta and may also involve the uterine corpus, cervix, or ovaries. It can be further divided into three types based on its appearance under the microscope:
	* Type I: Well-differentiated PSTN with a high degree of fetal trophoblast differentiation.
	* Type II: Moderately differentiated PSTN with some fetal trophoblast differentiation but also containing areas of poorly differentiated neoplasia.
	* Type III: Poorly differentiated PSTN with minimal or no fetal trophoblast differentiation and a higher risk of metastasis to distant organs.
2. Extra-placental trophoblastic neoplasia (EPTN): This subtype arises from the cells that form the chorion (the outermost layer of the placenta) and may involve other parts of the uterus, such as the uterine corpus or cervix. It can also spread to distant organs, such as the lungs or liver. EPTN is further divided into two types based on its appearance under the microscope:
	* Type A: Well-differentiated EPTN with a high degree of fetal trophoblast differentiation.
	* Type B: Poorly differentiated EPTN with minimal or no fetal trophoblast differentiation and a higher risk of metastasis to distant organs.
3. Placental-site mixed tumors (PSMT): This subtype is a combination of PSTN and other types of gestational trophoblastic neoplasia, such as EPTN or choriocarcinoma with squamous cell carcinoma. PSMT can be further divided into three types based on its appearance under the microscope:
	* Type I: Well-differentiated PSMT with a high degree of fetal trophoblast differentiation.
	* Type II: Moderately differentiated PSMT with some fetal trophoblast differentiation but also containing areas of poorly differentiated neoplasia, such as choriocarcinoma or squamous cell carcinoma.
	* Type III: Poorly differentiated PSMT with minimal or no fetal trophoblast differentiation and a higher risk of metastasis to distant organs.

Uterine corpus choriocarcinoma is a type of uterine cancer that originates in the uterus and has the specific location within the uterine corpus. It's important to note that while they may be related, choriocarcinoma and uterine corpus cancer are distinct conditions with different causes and treatments. Uterine corpus choriocarcinoma is a malignant tumor made up of trophoblastic cells, which can invade nearby tissues and spread to other parts of the body if left untreated. Proper diagnosis and treatment are crucial for effective management and recovery.

That is correct. Mediastinitis is a type of connective tissue disease that is characterized by inflammation located in the mediastinum, which extends from the diaphragm to the thoracic inlet and between the pleural cavities.

Myotonic cataract is a type of cataract that affects individuals with myotonic dystrophy. It is characterized by the iridescent opacification of the lens of the eye, which can cause multicolored vision. This condition can also lead to other vision problems and may require medical treatment.

Myocarditis is a condition in which the heart muscle becomes inflamed. It can cause chest pain, shortness of breath, and fatigue. Myocarditis is often caused by viral infections, but it can also be caused by bacterial or fungal infections, and less commonly by autoimmune disorders. Treatment for myocarditis typically involves medications to reduce inflammation and manage symptoms, and in some cases, hospitalization may be necessary. It is important to consult a healthcare professional if you suspect you have myocarditis.

Tertiary syphilis is a stage of the sexually transmitted infection syphilis. It follows the secondary stage, which is characterized by skin rash and other symptoms, and precedes the latent stage (when there are no symptoms). During tertiary syphilis, the infection spreads to various parts of the body, including the skeletal system, the cardiovascular system, and the nervous system. The disease can cause a range of serious health problems if left untreated, such as bone deformities, heart failure, blindness, and paralysis. It is important to get tested for syphilis early on in order to prevent the progression to tertiary syphilis and other advanced stages of the disease.

sacral spinal canal and spinal cord meningioma is a type of tumor that occurs in the sacral spinal canal and the spinal cord. It is also known as meningioma of the Sacral Spinal canal and Spinal Cord.

Hilar (or "Nonalo" in medical terms) lung carcinoma is a type of lung cancer that originates in the airways and blood vessels near the lungs. It's also referred to as non-small cell lung cancer when it's not classified as either squamous, large cell, or central lung carcinoma. Hilar lung carcinoma can occur in both smokers and nonsmokers, but is more common among those who have a history of heavy smoking. It often spreads to nearby lymph nodes and can also metastasize (spread) to other parts of the body, such as the brain or bones.

Lung superior sulcus carcinoma is a type of pancoast tumor, which is a rare and aggressive form of lung cancer that originates in the superior sulcus of the lung. The exact synonym for this type of cancer is "Superior Sulcus Carcinoma of the Lung." It is also related to "superior sulcus carcinoma of lung."

Fallopian tube cystadenofibroma is a type of fallopian tube adenofibroma.
Fallopian tube cystadenofibroma has the definition A fallopian tube adenofibroma that is characterized by the presence of cysts and/or cystic spaces..

Parapharyngeal meningioma is a type of meningioma that occurs in the area around the parapharyngeal space, which is located between the oropharynx and the nasopharynx. It is also sometimes called primary parapharyngeal meningioma to distinguish it from other types of meningioma that may arise from the dura mater or other parts of the brain. Symptoms of parapharyngeal meningioma can include hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, and ear pain, and treatment typically involves surgery to remove the tumor.

Upper clivus meningioma is a type of clivus meningioma that occurs in the upper part of the clivus, which is a portion of the skull located above the foramen magnum. Meningioma of the Upper Clivus refers specifically to a tumor that grows within this area. Both terms accurately describe the location and type of tumor.

central breast papilloma is a type of breast duct papilloma, which refers to the growth of abnormal cells in the ducts that carry milk from the lobules of the breast to the nipple. These ducts are called lactiferous ducts or tubules.
central breast papilloma is also known as a large duct breast papilloma, and it can occur when there is an excess of keratin in the duct, which can cause the cells to become abnormal.
Central breast papilloma usually doesn't cause any symptoms unless it becomes inflamed or infected. When that happens, it can cause a breast lump, nipple discharge, or skin changes around the breast. However, most central breast papillomas are small and don't cause any problems. If you have central breast papilloma, your doctor may recommend regular follow-up appointments to check for any changes.

Atypical breast papilloma is a type of breast duct papilloma. A breast duct papilloma refers to the growth of abnormal cells within a milk duct in the breast. While atypical breast papilloma is not yet malignant, it is still considered an abnormal growth and should be evaluated by a healthcare professional. It is important to note that some papillomas may become cancerous over time, so it's always best to consult with a medical professional for any abnormal breast changes.

Periapical periodontitis and apical periodontitis are terms used to describe inflammation of the tissues surrounding the teeth, specifically at the tip or root end. Both conditions refer to the infection and subsequent destruction of supporting structures around the affected tooth, often leading to pain, swelling, and even tooth loss if left untreated.

Treatment options for periapical periodontitis typically include scaling (removing plaque and tartar from the root surfaces), root planning (reshaping the root surfaces to remove any rough spots that could be trapping bacteria), and local antibiotics (to help combat bacterial infection). In severe cases, surgery may also be necessary.

It is important to note that while both periapical periodontitis and apical periodontitis refer to inflammation of the tissues surrounding the teeth at the root end, they are not interchangeable terms. Periapical periodontitis specifically refers to inflammation around the crown (visible part) of a tooth, while apical periodontitis is more general and encompasses inflammation at any point along the root surface, including the crown.

intrahepatic biliary papillomatosis is a type of biliary papillomatosis that occurs when there are many growths in the intrahepatic bile duct. It can be caused by chronic inflammation and infection, as well as certain medications. Treatment may involve surgery or other interventions to remove the affected tissue.

lower clivus meningioma is a type of meningioma that occurs in the lower Clivus area of the brain. It is also known as the meningioma of the lower Clivus. Meningioma is a type of tumor that originates from the meninges, which are the protective coverings of the brain and spinal cord. The Clivus is a bony structure in the middle of the skull, located between the brainstem and the cerebellum. Lower clivus meningioma can cause symptoms such as headache, nausea, vomiting, balance problems, and difficulty swallowing. It is typically treated with surgery, although radiation therapy or other forms of treatment may also be used in some cases.

Yes, periodontitis is a type of periodontal disease that affects the gums and jawbone around the teeth. Chronic pericementitis is a different condition characterized by inflammation of the dentin in the tooth root. While they share some similarities, they are distinct diseases with different causes and treatments. Periodontitis typically results from poor oral hygiene practices, while chronic pericementitis is believed to be caused by bacterial infections in the root canal of the tooth. Treatment for periodontitis often involves deep cleaning and regular dental check-ups, whereas treatment for chronic pericementitis may involve endodontic therapy or tooth extraction.

Meningeal melanomatosis is a type of central nervous system (CNS) melanocytic neoplasm. It is characterized as an extra-axial, well-encapsulated malignant tumor with diffuse meningeal growth and dark coloration due to high melanin content. The exact synonym for this condition is Leptomeningeal melanomatosis.

Adult Pleomorphic Rhabdomyosarcoma is a subtype of Pleomorphic Rhabdomyosarcoma, which is a type of sarcoma that develops from muscle tissue. Adult onset refers to the age at which the cancer starts, which in this case is during adulthood (typically after the age of 18).

Chronic rhinitis is a type of rhinitis that has symptoms such as nasal congestion and discharge. It can occur with certain diseases like syphilis, tuberculosis, and leprosy, which are characterized by the formation of inflamed lesions (granulomas) and the destruction of soft tissue, cartilage, and bone. Chronic rhinitis causes persistent nasal congestion, pus-filled discharge from the nose, and frequent bleeding.

Vulva Fibroepithelial Polyp (VFP) is a type of vulvar disease characterized by the overgrowth of fibrous tissue in the vulvar area. It can cause discomfort, pain, and irritation. VFPs are usually benign growths but can sometimes be precancerous or cancerous if left untreated. They are typically diagnosed through a biopsy and treated with surgical removal. Early detection and treatment of VFPs is important to prevent the development of more severe conditions.

ureter tuberculosis (tuberculosis of ureter) is a type of urogenital tuberculosis that occurs when the bacteria Mycobacterium tuberculosis infects the ureters, which are the tubes that transport urine from the kidneys to the bladder. This infection can cause inflammation and scarring of the ureter walls, leading to a narrowing or obstruction of the ureter (ureteral strictures). Tuberculosis of the ureters is an uncommon form of tuberculosis that affects both sexes but is more common in women. It can also cause infertility due to blockage and damage to the reproductive organs, and may lead to kidney failure if left untreated. Ureter tuberculosis can be treated with antibiotics, surgery, or a combination of both.

Yes, anterior urethra cancer is indeed a type of female urethral cancer. The definition of anterior urethra cancer refers to the malignant tumor located in the anterior part of the female urethra. There is no other information provided about the term "anterior urethra cancer."

Synovial angioma is a type of connective tissue benign neoplasm that refers to the growth of abnormal blood vessels within the synovial membrane. It is also known as hemangioma of the synovium, and it can cause various symptoms depending on its location and size. The condition typically affects middle-aged adults and can be diagnosed through imaging tests such as ultrasound or MRI. Treatment options may include surgical excision or other minimally invasive procedures to remove the affected tissue.

Intratubular embryonal carcinoma is a subtype of embryonal testis carcinoma, which is a type of cancer that affects the testes in children. It gets its name from the fact that it forms within tubules, which are small structures found within the testes. This particular subtype of cancer is characterized by the presence of tumor cells that have a certain level of differentiation and can potentially grow and spread to other areas of the body. However, with proper treatment, intratubular embryonal carcinoma has a relatively good prognosis compared to some other types of testicular cancer.

Adult epithelioid sarcoma is a type of soft tissue sarcoma that typically affects individuals in their adult years. It originates from the epithelial tissue and can occur in various locations throughout the body, such as the arms, legs, chest, abdomen, or head and neck. The tumors are usually round or lobulated and range in size from a few centimeters to several meters.

Epithelioid sarcoma is characterized by a unique cellular appearance with abundant pale eosinophilic cytoplasm, which distinguishes it from other types of sarcomas. It also has a specific set of genetic and molecular markers that help in its diagnosis. Treatment options for adult epithelioid sarcoma may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination thereof, depending on the stage and location of the tumor.

It's important to note that while this information is accurate at the time of writing (March 2023), medical research is constantly evolving, and new discoveries might impact the understanding and treatment of adult epithelioid sarcoma in the future.

Peritonitis is a type of gastrointestinal system disease that involves inflammation of the peritoneum, which is the lining that surrounds and supports the abdominal organs. This can occur due to various causes such as perforation of the gastrointestinal tract or other conditions like appendicitis, diverticulitis, strangulating intestinal obstruction, pancreatitis, pelvic inflammatory disease, mesenteric ischemia, intraperitoneal blood, barium, or peritoneo-systemic shunts, drains, and dialysis catheters in the peritoneal cavity.
Symptoms of peritonitis include abdominal pain and tenderness, fever, fluid in the abdomen, nausea, vomiting, and low urine output. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have peritonitis as it can be a serious condition that requires treatment.

Clear cell squamous cell carcinoma (CCSCC) of the skin is a type of non-melanoma skin cancer characterized by abnormal growth and spread of squamous cells in the upper layers of the skin. It is also known as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma or keratoacanthoma, and can be caused by prolonged sun exposure, aging, immunosuppressive drugs, and other factors. CCSCC is often diagnosed through biopsy and treated with surgical removal of the affected skin, along with a margin of healthy tissue. In some cases, radiation therapy or topical chemotherapy may also be used to treat the cancer. It is important to note that early detection and treatment are crucial in achieving the best possible outcome for patients with CCSCC.

Scabies is a type of mite infestation that can cause severe itching and a rash on the skin. It is caused by the mite Sarcoptes scabiei var hominis, which burrows into the upper layer of the skin and can affect various areas of the body including the hands, wrists, elbows, knees, penis, breasts, and shoulders. This infestation is contagious and can be spread through close contact with an infected individual or by sharing clothing and bedding. Treatment for scabies typically involves using prescription medications to kill the mites and their eggs, as well as washing and cleaning any affected items or surfaces.
Cataract is a type of monogenic disease that affects the lens inside the eye. It causes clouding, which leads to a decrease in vision. Cataract has an exact match in MESH: D002386.
Stromomyoma is a type of uterine corpus cancer that has material basis in endometrial stroma and smooth muscle cells. It is also known as mixed endometrial stromal and smooth muscle tumor.

Congenital granular cell tumor is a type of physical disorder, specifically a benign tumor that affects the bone marrow. It is also known as congenital granuloma or congenital granulomatosis. The exact cause of this condition is not well understood, but it occurs when an area of bone marrow becomes overgrown with abnormal cells. This can lead to problems with blood cell production and affect the overall health of the individual. Treatment options depend on the size and location of the tumor, as well as the underlying health of the patient.

Palisaded myofibroblastoma of the lymph node is a type of benign neoplasm that originates in the lymphatic system. It is characterized by the presence of spindle cells, which are specialized cells found in the connective tissue of the lymph nodes. These cells have a palisading pattern, which means they are arranged around central blood vessels in layers. The term "amyloid" is also sometimes used to describe these cells because they can sometimes contain protein deposits that give them a yellow or amber color. This condition is not cancerous and typically does not spread beyond the affected lymph node. However, it can cause enlargement of the lymph node and may require surgical removal if it becomes too large or causes other symptoms.

Yes, a nonossifying fibromyxoid tumor is indeed a type of mesenchymal cell neoplasm. It is characterized by the presence of both fibrous tissue and cartilage-like materials within the tumor. The term "nonossifying" refers to the fact that this type of tumor does not produce bone, unlike other types of tumors such as osteosarcoma which do produce bone.

The exact synonym for a nonossifying fibromyxoid tumor is indeed "Nonossifying Fibromyxoma". This term is often used interchangeably with the more commonly used term "fibromyxoid tumor" to describe a similar type of lesion. It's important to note that these tumors can occur in various locations within the body, including the jaw, skull, and other bones.

If you have any further questions or concerns about nonossifying fibromyxoid tumors, please feel free to ask!

Early invasive cervical adenocarcinoma is a type of cervical cancer that is characterized by tumor cells that are similar to those found in adenocarcinoma in situ (ACIS) and microscopic findings that suggest the cancer has begun to spread beyond the surface layer of the cervix.

Sclerosing adenosis of the breast is a type of proliferative benign breast condition characterized by the presence of enlarged lobules that are distorted by scar-like tissue and excess glandular tissue. The term "sclerosing" refers to the formation of dense, fibrous tissue, while "adenosis" refers to the presence of abnormal breast tissue.

Sclerosing adenosis of the breast is also known as fibrocystic change with sclerosis, which occurs when there is an excessive buildup of fibrous tissue within the breast lobules. This condition can cause discomfort or pain and may require monitoring or treatment if it progresses to a more advanced stage.

It's important to note that while this condition may be concerning, it is typically benign and not cancerous. However, if you have concerns about your breast health, it's always best to speak with your healthcare provider for proper evaluation and guidance.

Cancer of the auditory system, also known as otoracochordomas or chordomas, is a rare type of cancer that affects the bones and soft tissues surrounding the ear. These tumors typically grow slowly and can cause symptoms such as hearing loss, dizziness, and balance problems. Auditory system cancer often occurs at the intersection of the skull base and the auditory canal, which makes it challenging to remove the entire tumor with surgery alone. Treatment for this type of cancer typically involves a combination of surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy to ensure that all cancer cells are removed or destroyed.

Perineural angioma, also known as a meningioma, is a type of central nervous system (CNS) tumor that originates from the perineural vascular plexus. The term "perineural" refers to the presence of blood vessels surrounding or near nerve roots in the spinal cord and brainstem. These tumors are typically benign, but can cause compression on surrounding structures leading to symptoms such as headaches, vision changes, and weakness in certain areas of the body.

Appendicitis is a medical condition that occurs when the appendix becomes inflamed and infected due to blockage or infection by bacteria, viruses or parasites. Symptoms of Appendicitis include pain in the lower right abdomen, nausea, vomiting, fever, loss of appetite, and a feeling of general malaise. It is often diagnosed through imaging techniques such as ultrasound, CT scan or MRI. The treatment for appendicitis typically involves surgical removal of the inflamed appendix through an incision in the abdomen with general anesthesia.

Villoglandular variant cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma is a specific subtype of cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of thin, simple papillary structures without broad, fibrovascular cores. It is considered to be well differentiated and has a relatively favorable prognosis compared to other subtypes of cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma.
intestinal variant cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma is a specific type of cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma characterized by intestinal-type differentiation.

endocervical type cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma is a rare subtype of cervical cancer. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy.

It has the exact synonym of "complement component 3 deficiency."

Lumbar plexus neoplasm is a type of nerve plexus neoplasm that occurs in the lumbar region of the spine. It is characterized by the abnormal growth of cells in the Lumbar Plexus, which can cause compression and irritation of the spinal nerves.
Tumor of Lumbar Plexus refers to a specific type of lumbar plexus neoplasm that is composed of malignant (cancerous) cells. It is important to note that not all lumbar plexus neoplasms are cancerous, and some may be benign (non-cancerous).
It's essential for patients with suspected lumbar plexus neoplasm to undergo a thorough diagnostic evaluation by a qualified medical professional, including imaging studies such as MRI or CT scans, and biopsy if necessary. Adult Type Testicular Granulosa Cell Tumor (AGT) is a type of ovarian granulosa cell tumor that typically affects adult females. It is a rare and aggressive form of cancer, which can spread rapidly to other organs in the body. The exact cause of AGT is unknown, but it may be linked to genetic factors or exposure to certain chemicals. Symptoms of AGT include abdominal pain, bloating, weight loss, and a feeling of fullness. Diagnosis is made through a combination of physical examination, imaging tests, and biopsy. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy. It's important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment planning.
Osteoarthritis is a type of arthritis that occurs when the cartilage in a joint wears out over time. It can cause pain, stiffness, and swelling in the affected joint.

Correct, trombiculiasis is a type of mite infestation caused by the Leptotrombidium deliense mite. This mite can cause a skin rash and other symptoms in people who come into contact with it. It's also known as "scrub typhus" or "trombiculosis." Is there anything else you would like to know about trombiculiasis?

Osteochondritis dissecans is a condition that affects the joint, specifically the epiphysis (the growth plate at the end of a bone). It occurs when there is limited blood flow to the affected area, causing damage and possibly resulting in necrosis (death of cells). The disease can cause pain and swelling in the affected joint. Treatment options depend on the severity of the condition and may include medication, physical therapy, or surgery.

Cork handlers disease is an extrinsic allergic alveolitis caused by inhalation of cork dust containing the antigens produced by the fungus Penicillium glabrum. The symptoms include dyspnea, wheezing, cough, fever, and asthenia. It has exact synonyms such as suberosis, cork-handlers' disease or lung, and cork-handlers' lung.

Malignant cornea melanoma, also known as malignant Corneal melanoma or malignant Melanoma of the cornea, is a rare and aggressive type of cancer that affects the eye. It originates in the pigment-producing cells of the cornea (melanin-containing epithelial cells). These cells are responsible for producing the brown or black pigment found in human skin.

Malignant cornea melanoma can cause a variety of symptoms, including pain, redness, and blurriness. In some cases, it may also present as a white or grey area on the eye. The exact cause of this cancer is unknown; however, genetic factors, exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation, and certain types of trauma have been linked to its development.

If malignant cornea melanoma is detected early enough, it can be treated with surgical procedures such as enucleation or eyelid exenteration. However, if the cancer has spread beyond the eye or to other parts of the body, more aggressive treatments like chemotherapy or radiation therapy may be necessary. It is important for individuals who notice any symptoms of malignant cornea melanoma to consult with an ophthalmologist or other healthcare professional as soon as possible to receive proper diagnosis and treatment.

Meckel's diverticulitis is a type of diverticulitis that affects the cecum, which is the beginning of the large intestine. It occurs when a small pouch or sac forms in the cecal region and becomes inflamed. This condition can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, constipation, and diarrhea. Treatment typically involves dietary changes, antibiotics, and sometimes surgery to remove the affected portion of the intestine. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Microinvasive cervical squamous cell carcinoma is a type of cervical cancer that has limited invasion into the surrounding tissues, as determined by microscopy. It is typically diagnosed when the tumor measures between 3mm and 5mm in diameter with a maximum depth of 7mm. This type of cancer is less aggressive than invasive cervical squamous cell carcinoma and often requires less extensive treatment.

Extrinsic allergic alveolitis is an interstitial lung disease that involves inflammation of the alveoli and bronchioles in the lungs due to an allergic reaction to inhaled organic dusts containing microorganisms or proteins, and chemicals. It can cause symptoms such as chills, cough, fever, malaise, shortness of breath, loss of appetite, and weight loss. The disease has a definition that it is an interstitial lung disease involving inflammation of alveoli and smallest airways (bronchioles) of the lung caused by an allergic reaction to inhaled organic dusts containing microorganisms or proteins, and chemicals. It has an exact synonym of alveolitis and hypersensitivity pneumonitis is also a good term to describe this disease.
Childhood kidney angiomyolipoma is a type of renal Angiomyolipoma that occurs during childhood. It is also known as pediatric renal Angiomyolipoma.

Angiomyolipoma of the kidney, also known as renal Angiomyolipoma, is a benign neoplasm characterized by the presence of blood vessels (capillaries), fat cells (lipocytes), and fibrous tissue in the kidneys. It is also referred to simply as an angiomyolipoma or kidney AML. These tumors are typically solitary, although multiple tumors can occur together in a condition called multiple renal Angiomyolipomas. They usually measure less than 4 cm in diameter and are slow-growing.

Congenital fibrosarcoma, also known as infantile fibrosarcoma, is a type of malignant tumor that affects children. It typically develops during childhood and is characterized by the excessive growth of fibrous tissue in the affected area. This abnormal growth can lead to the formation of a mass or lump that may cause pain, swelling, or other symptoms. Congenital fibrosarcoma is often treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy, depending on the location, size, and stage of the tumor. It is important for children with congenital fibrosarcoma to receive appropriate medical care to ensure the best possible outcome.

Colloid adenoma is a type of follicular adenoma, which is characterized by the presence of multiple small cystic spaces or glands within the tumor. It may be associated with hormonal imbalances and can cause symptoms such as acne, excessive hair growth, and irregular menstrual cycles in women.
Macrofollicular adenoma is another term for colloid adenoma, which refers to a type of benign tumor that is composed of numerous follicles or cysts. These tumors can cause various symptoms depending on their size and location, including skin problems such as acne and rosacea, as well as hormonal imbalances that may affect menstrual cycles in women.
Both colloid adenoma and macrofollicular adenoma are generally considered benign tumors, but they can still cause significant discomfort and require treatment to prevent complications such as scarring or infection.

Malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors (MPNST) are a type of soft tissue sarcoma that arise from the peripheral nerves. They can occur in both children and adults, but are more common in children. MPNSTs can be classified into two main types: malignant glandular tumor of peripheral nerve sheath (MPNST) and malignant fibrous histiocytoma (MFH).

MPNSTs are characterized by their aggressive behavior and high rate of recurrence, even after surgical resection. They often spread to nearby tissues and organs, as well as distant sites in the body through blood and lymph channels.

Treatment for MPNST typically involves a multidisciplinary approach, including surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and/or immunotherapy. The prognosis for patients with MPNST is generally poor, with a survival rate of less than 50% even with aggressive treatment.

It's important to note that the exact cause of MPNST is not known, but researchers believe that genetic and environmental factors may play a role in its development. Early detection and prompt treatment are crucial for improving outcomes for patients with this rare and aggressive tumor type.

Breast apocrine carcinoma in situ is a type of breast carcinoma in situ, which is characterized by the presence of abundant eosinophilic apocrine cytoplasm and large nuclei. It is considered a variant of ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) of the breast. Apocrine carcinoma in situ of the breast is its exact synonym.

afferent loop syndrome is a rare condition that occurs when the stomach's normal function of producing acid is disrupted. This can happen after surgery to remove part of the stomach, such as a gastrectomy. As a result, food may not be properly digested and the patient may experience symptoms like abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Treatment options for afferent loop syndrome usually involve managing symptoms and avoiding certain foods that can trigger them.

Postgastrectomy syndrome is a condition that affects the stomach after gastric bypass surgery. It is caused by changes in the way the stomach and intestines function after the surgery, which can lead to problems such as difficulty swallowing, bloating, abdominal pain, and a feeling of fullness even after eating small amounts of food. Postgastrectomy syndrome is also known as postgastric surgery syndrome.

Ileus of intestine is a specific condition characterized by obstruction of the small intestine, usually caused by adhesions, scar tissue, or inflammation. It can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, distension, vomiting, and difficulty in passing stools. Ileus is another term used to describe a similar condition, but it is more general and could refer to any type of intestinal obstruction.

It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms of volvulus, such as abdominal pain, vomiting, and difficulty passing gas or stools. Treatment options for volvulus typically involve surgery to correct the twisting of the intestines and restore normal function.

Cyclothymic disorder is a type of bipolar disorder characterized by recurrent hypomanic and dysthymic episodes, but without full manic or major depressive episodes. It is also known as affective personality disorder, cycloid personality, cyclothymia, or simply cyclothymic personality disorder.

Riboflavin deficiency is a type of nutritional deficiency disease that can cause various symptoms, including conjunctivitis, anemia, fatigue, pharynx inflammation, angular cheilitis, glossitis, and stomatitis. It develops from a lack of vitamin B2 (riboflavin) in the diet or due to certain medical conditions such as endocrine disorders, liver disorders, alcoholism, or dialysis. Symptoms can include red chapped lips, painful swollen tongue, sore throat, blurred vision, and fatigue.

Pyridoxine Deficiency Anemia is a type of nutritional deficiency disease that occurs as a result of inadequate intake, malabsorption, increased clearance or breakdown, and certain medications (such as isoniazid). It is characterized by normocytic anemia, which means that the red blood cells are normal in size but low in hemoglobin. Hemoglobin is a protein found in red blood cells that carries oxygen throughout the body. A deficiency of pyridoxine (vitamin B6) can lead to this type of anemia, as it plays a crucial role in the production of red blood cells and maintaining normal hemoglobin levels. It is important to note that Pyridoxine Deficiency Anemia can be prevented or treated by increasing pyridoxine intake through diet or supplements, and addressing any underlying causes of malabsorption or increased clearance.

Aicardi syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the brain and the eyes. Retinal degeneration refers to a group of eye diseases that affect the retina, the light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye. It is characterized by progressive deterioration and eventual death of cells in the retina, leading to a loss of vision. There are several types of retinal degeneration, including age-related macular degeneration (AMD), which is the most common cause of vision loss in people over 65 years of age. Other types include congenital retinal degeneration, which is present at birth and can lead to blindness, and retinal detachment, which occurs when the retina detaches from its underlying tissue. Treatment options for retinal degeneration may include eye vitamins, laser therapy, or surgical interventions, depending on the specific type and severity of the disease.

Influenza is a viral infectious disease that affects the respiratory system and has symptoms such as severe headache, weakness, rhinorrhea, fever, cough, muscle pain, chills, pharynx inflammation, and sore throat. It is highly contagious and can be transmitted through droplet spread from infected individuals who cough, sneeze or talk.

text:
Scleroderma is a chronic connective tissue disease that results in the thickening and hardening of the skin, as well as other organs. It can be classified into two main types: localized and diffuse.

Localized scleroderma, also known as Morphea, circumscribed or localised scleroderma, is a type of scleroderma that affects only one area of the body, usually the arms, legs, or trunk. It is characterized by the formation of firm, raised areas on the skin, which can be itchy and painful. Localized scleroderma typically does not cause significant internal organ involvement.

Diffuse scleroderma, also known as systemic sclerosis, involves the entire body and affects multiple organs, including the lungs, kidneys, gastrointestinal tract, and blood vessels. It is characterized by the thickening of the skin, which can become hard and tight, as well as the development of Raynaud's phenomenon (a condition that causes changes in blood flow to the fingers and toes). Diffuse scleroderma can lead to more severe complications, such as pulmonary arterial hypertension and renal crisis.

It is important for individuals with scleroderma to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage their symptoms and prevent potential complications. Treatment may include medications to reduce inflammation or slow down the thickening of the skin, as well as physical therapy to improve mobility and strength.

Whipple's disease, also known as intestinal lipodystrophy, is a type of intestinal disease characterized by the loss of fat cells in the body. It primarily affects the small intestine and can cause a variety of symptoms including diarrhea, abdominal pain, and weight loss. The exact cause of Whipple's disease is not fully understood, but it is thought to be caused by a bacterial infection, most commonly with the bacterium Tropheryma whipplei. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and other medications to manage symptoms and support recovery.

Actinomycosis is a type of bacterial infection caused by the growth of Actinomyces israelii and other similar species. It typically affects the respiratory system, causing symptoms such as coughing up blood, chest pain, fever, and difficulty breathing. The disease can also cause abscesses and granulomas to form in various parts of the body. Treatment usually involves a course of antibiotics and surgery to drain any infected areas. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have Actinomycosis, as it can be life-threatening if left untreated.

Arthritis is a common condition that affects the joints and causes inflammation, pain, and stiffness. It can be caused by various factors such as age, genetics, obesity, and injury to the joint. There are different types of arthritis, including osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis, gout, and psoriatic arthritis. Osteoarthritis is the most common type of arthritis and occurs due to the wear and tear of cartilage in the joints. Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disorder where the body's immune system attacks the lining of the joint, leading to inflammation and pain. Gout is a type of arthritis that occurs due to high levels of uric acid in the blood, which can form crystals in the joint and cause pain and swelling. Psoriatic arthritis is a type of arthritis that affects people with psoriasis, causing inflammation in the joints. Treatment for arthritis depends on the type and severity of the disease, but it can include medications, physical therapy, and lifestyle changes to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Rheumatic myocarditis is a type of bacterial infections that affects the heart muscle. It is caused by the streptococcus pyogenes bacteria, and can lead to inflammation and damage to the myocardium. This condition has exact synonyms such as rheumatic degeneration of myocardium, rheumatic fever with myocarditis, rheumatoid myocarditis, active rheumatic fever with myocarditis, and acute rheumatic carditis or acute rheumatic myocarditis.

Transient retinal arterial occlusion, also known as transient arterial retinal occlusion, is a type of retinal artery occlusion. It occurs when there is a temporary blockage of the blood flow to the eye's retina, caused by a clot or other obstruction in one of the retinal arteries. The symptoms typically appear suddenly and can include vision loss, floaters, and pain or pressure in the affected eye. However, these symptoms are usually temporary and may resolve on their own within a few days to weeks. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience any of these symptoms to determine the cause and receive appropriate treatment.

Retinal artery occlusion (RAO) is a medical condition where the blood flow to the retina is obstructed. It occurs when there is a blockage or narrowing in one of the arteries that supply blood to the eye. The retina relies on a constant supply of oxygen and nutrients, so when the blood flow is disrupted, it can cause damage to the retinal cells and potentially lead to vision loss if left untreated.
RAO is often caused by atherosclerosis, which is the build-up of plaque in the arteries due to a buildup of fat, cholesterol, and other substances. Other possible causes include emboli (blood clots or foreign substances that travel through the bloodstream), trauma, and inflammatory conditions such as vasculitis.
Diagnosis typically involves a comprehensive eye exam, including visual acuity testing, dilated fundus photography, and optical coherence tomography (OCT). Treatment options may include medications to manage blood pressure and cholesterol levels, surgical procedures such as angioplasty or stent placement to open the blocked artery, and laser treatment to seal off a smaller vessel that is causing the blockage. It's important to seek medical attention promptly if you experience symptoms of RAO, as early detection and treatment can help prevent further vision loss.

Maple bark strippers lung is a type of opportunistic mycosis, which is located in the lungs and caused by inhalation of fungal spores while stripping the bark from maple logs. It has a material basis in Cryptostroma corticale. The disease is also known as Maple bark-strippers' lung, alveolitis due to cryptostroma corticale, and maple bark disease or maple bark stripper's disease.

Mucormycosis is a type of opportunistic fungal infection that occurs primarily in immunocompromised individuals. It results from an infection with molds belonging to the Mucorales family, which are commonly found in soil and water. The infection can spread throughout the body, including the sinuses, brain, and lungs. Disseminated mucormycosis and zygomycosis are other terms used to describe this condition.

That is correct. Polyhydramnios is a condition in which there is an excess of amniotic fluid in the amniotic sac, which can lead to complications for both the mother and the baby. It occurs when the placenta doesn't function properly or there is a problem with the development of the fetus that causes increased fluid production.

Rheumatoid Arthritis Interstitial Lung Disease is an autoimmune disease that affects the musculoskeletal system. It is characterized by abnormal immunoglobulin levels and can lead to pleuroparenchymal disease, including pleural effusions, pulmonary vascular disease, and airway complications. The exact synonym for this condition is Rheumatoid Lung.

Hereditary night blindness is a type of night blindness that is passed down through genetics. It can be caused by mutations in certain genes that are responsible for the development and function of the eyes. Congenital night blindness, on the other hand, refers specifically to the condition where an individual is born with a significant degree of difficulty seeing in low light conditions. While both hereditary and congenital night blindness can cause difficulty seeing in the dark, they are distinct conditions with different underlying causes and may require different treatment approaches.
Night blindness is a type of retinal disease that is characterized by difficulty or the inability to see in relatively low light. It is also known as nyctalopia.

Lung disease encompasses a wide range of conditions that affect the lungs and airways, including asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, and pneumonia. These diseases can cause various symptoms such as shortness of breath, coughing, wheezing, and chest tightness. In some cases, lung disease can also affect the heart and other organs in the body. Treatment options depend on the specific type of lung disease and may include medications, lifestyle changes, and surgery. It's important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Fundus dystrophy, also known as retinal dystrophy, is a condition where the retina does not function properly. The retina is located at the back of the eye and is responsible for processing light signals before they are transmitted to the brain through the optic nerve. When the retina malfunctions, it can result in vision loss or blindness. There are various types of fundus dystrophy, including inherited forms that are passed down through families and acquired forms caused by other medical conditions such as diabetes or hypertension. Treatment options may vary depending on the underlying cause but generally include medications to slow the progression of the disease or surgery to correct any structural issues affecting the retina.

Bullous skin disease is a condition characterized by the formation of large, fluid-filled blisters on the skin. It can be caused by various factors such as allergic reactions, autoimmune disorders, and exposure to certain chemicals or substances. Bullous skin disease is considered a type of dermatitis, which refers to inflammation of the skin. The disease is often associated with an excessive intake of gluten, although this is not always the case. Treatment options may include topical steroids, immunosuppressants, and changes in diet.
Impetigo herpetiformis is a form of severe pustular psoriasis that occurs during pregnancy.

Impetigo is a skin condition characterized by itchy, red, and sometimes swollen skin that can develop into blisters or sores. It's caused by bacteria and can be contagious. There are three types of impetigo:

1. Common (or superficial) impetigo: This is the most common type of impetigo. It causes a thick, adherent, recurrent, dirty yellow crust with an erythematous margin.
2. Bullous (or staphylococcal) impetigo: This type of impetigo causes superficial, thin-walled, and bullous lesions. It is always caused by Staphylococcus aureus bacteria.
3. Ecthyma: This is a more severe form of impetigo that causes deeper, wet, and purple-colored lesions. It can be caused by the same bacteria as common impetigo or other types of staphylococcus bacteria.

Impetigo is typically treated with antibiotics to kill the bacteria causing the infection. In some cases, a healthcare provider may recommend a prescription-strength topical antibiotic cream or ointment for more severe cases.

Dermatitis herpetiformis is a chronic autoimmune skin condition that causes small, itchy blisters on the skin. It is often seen in people with celiac disease or gluten sensitivity. The exact synonyms for Dermatitis Herpetiformis are Dermatosis Herpetiformis and Duhring's disease.
That is correct, Bullous pemphigoid is a type of pemphigoid characterized by the presence of large blisters.
Juvenile dermatitis herpetiformis (JDH) is a type of dermatitis herpetiformis that begins during childhood or adolescence.

Subcorneal pustular dermatosis is a type of bullous skin disease characterized by the formation of pus-filled blisters on the top layer of the skin (the epidermis). It is also known as Sneddon-Wilkinson disease or syndrome. This condition can be caused by various factors, including exposure to certain chemicals or drugs, infections, and autoimmune disorders. The symptoms of subcorneal pustular dermatosis typically include itchy, red, and swollen skin with the formation of pus-filled blisters. If you suspect that you have this condition, it is important to seek medical attention as soon as possible to receive an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.

Bartholin's duct cyst (BDC) is a type of Bartholin's gland disease. BDC occurs when the duct that carries the fluid from the gland becomes inflamed or blocked, causing it to swell up and form a cyst. This condition primarily affects women and can cause symptoms such as pain, itching, and discomfort during sexual intercourse. However, most BDCs are harmless and resolve on their own without treatment. If the cyst becomes infected or large enough to cause problems, it may need to be drained or removed surgically.

Cor pulmonale is a specific type of congestive heart failure that occurs when the right side of the heart fails due to increased resistance or high blood pressure in the lungs. It is characterized by an enlargement of the right ventricle of the heart as a response to these conditions. Other synonyms for cor pulmonale include cardiopulmonary disease and pulmonary heart disease.

Barbiturate abuse is defined as the recurring use of barbiturate drugs despite negative consequences.

Monocytic leukemia is a type of myeloid leukemia characterized by an excessive production of immature white blood cells called monocytes. It can lead to anemia, infections, and increased risk of bleeding due to the low levels of other types of blood cells. Treatment typically involves chemotherapy and bone marrow transplantation.

An ulcer of the lower limbs, also known as a non-decubitus ulcer of the foot or ankle, is a chronic skin condition characterized by an ongoing open sore that does not heal. The affected skin can become thin and susceptible to infections. This type of ulcer typically develops slowly over time and may be caused by various factors such as poor blood circulation, pressure injuries, or infection with bacteria or viruses. Treatment options for an ulcer of the lower limbs may include wound care, debridement, antibiotics, and supportive measures to manage pain and promote healing. In some cases, surgical intervention may also be necessary to address underlying issues such as infection or tissue damage.

Polymyalgia rheumatica is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the musculoskeletal system. It is characterized by pain and stiffness in the shoulders, neck, hips, and other proximal muscle groups. It is also associated with an elevated level of immunoglobulin in the blood. The exact cause of polymyalgia rheumatica is not known, but it is thought to be triggered by a combination of genetic and environmental factors.

Hypopharynx cancer is a type of pharyngeal cancer that occurs in the hypopharynx, which is the lowest part of the pharynx that connects the throat to the trachea. The hypopharynx is also known as the laryngopharynx or supraglottic area. It is a malignant tumor of the hypopharynx and can be treated with surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these treatments.

text: gastroesophageal reflux disease, also known as GERD, is a condition in which stomach acid flows back into the esophagus. This can cause heartburn and other symptoms.

Herpes zoster is a viral infectious disease that results from the reactivation of the varicella-zoster virus, which causes chickenpox in childhood. The virus is transmitted through direct contact with the rash, which can develop into chickenpox in newly-infected individuals. Herpes zoster typically presents with a painful, itchy rash that follows nerve paths, and often accompanies other symptoms such as headache, fever, malaise, itching, burning pain, and paresthesia. It has a material basis in the human alphaherpesvirus 3 and can be diagnosed through skin biopsy or PCR testing. The disease primarily affects the nervous system, but can also cause systemic symptoms such as fever and malaise.

Reticulosarcoma is a rare type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system, and it can also be referred to as histiocytic lymphoma or large-cell lymphomas. It primarily develops in the lymph nodes and spleen, and it can spread to other parts of the body if left untreated. Treatment options for reticulosarcoma may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, immunotherapy, or a combination of these treatments. It is essential to consult with a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Collagen disease, also known as a collagen disorder, is a type of connective tissue disease. It is characterized by inheritable defects in the collagen protein found in the body's connective tissues. These defects can lead to the breakdown and weakening of these tissues, which are essential for maintaining the structure and function of various organs and body parts. There are many different types of collagen diseases, each with its own specific symptoms and treatments. Some common examples include Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (EDS), Marfan syndrome, and osteogenesis imperfecta.

Sezary disease, also known as Sezary syndrome, is a type of primary cutaneous T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma. It is characterized by the presence of malignant T cells in the skin and blood. The disease can affect people of all ages but is most common in adults. It has been linked to exposure to sunlight, Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and certain medications. Symptoms may include itchy skin, scaly patches or bumps on the skin, fever, night sweats, weight loss, and fatigue. Treatment options include chemotherapy, immunotherapy, and targeted therapies such as rituximab.

Hodgkin lymphoma, also known as Hodgkin's disease, is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system. It is characterized by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells, which are large, abnormal B cells that are surrounded by inflammatory cells such as T cells and macrophages.
Hodgkin's disease can be classified into four stages (I, II, III, and IV), with stage IV being the most advanced and life-threatening. Treatment options may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, immunotherapy, and sometimes surgery or stem cell transplantation. The prognosis of Hodgkin's disease varies depending on the stage at diagnosis and other factors such as age and overall health.
It is important to note that Hodgkin lymphoma can also be classified into different subtypes based on the types of cells involved, including classic Hodgkin lymphoma, nodular sclerosing Hodgkin lymphoma, and lymphocytic-histiocytic predominance Hodgkin lymphoma.

Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS) is a condition that is characterized by persistent and debilitating fatigue, which is not improved by rest and can last for at least six months. It is also referred to as Myalgic Encephalomyelitis (ME), Post-Viral Fatigue Syndrome (PVFS), or Chronic Fatigue Immune Dysfunction Syndrome (CFIDS).

Malignant hyperthermia is a type of muscle tissue disease that is characterized by a drastic and uncontrolled increase in skeletal muscle oxidative metabolism, which overwhelms the body's capacity to supply oxygen, remove carbon dioxide, and regulate body temperature. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ryanodine receptor gene (RYR1) on chromosome 19q13. Manifestations of malignant hyperthermia are precipitated by certain volatile anesthetics, either alone or in conjunction with a depolarizing muscle relaxant such as succinylcholine. Malignant hyperthermia is also known as anesthesia-related hyperthermia and malignant hyperpyrexia due to anesthesia.

Chronic ulcer of skin, also known as callous ulcer or indolent ulcer, is a type of skin disease characterized by the slow and gradual healing of skin wounds. These wounds may be caused by various factors such as pressure ulcers, infections, or autoimmune disorders. The symptoms of chronic ulcer of skin include the presence of an open sore or lesion that is slow to heal and may be accompanied by redness, pus, or a foul-smelling discharge. Treatment for chronic ulcer of skin typically involves debridement (removal of dead tissue) and wound dressings, as well as antibiotics if there is an infection present. In some cases, surgery may also be necessary to remove the affected tissue.

text: Chronic myeloid leukemia is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood. It's characterized by an uncontrolled growth of white blood cells, specifically granulocytes. The condition is caused by a mutation in the Philadelphia chromosome, which results in the production of an abnormal protein called Bcr-Abl. This protein disrupts normal cell signaling and causes the leukemia cells to multiply uncontrollably. Chronic myeloid leukemia can be treated with chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and bone marrow transplantation.

Pyoderma gangrenosum is a type of skin disease characterized by the sudden onset of fever, skin eruptions, and rapid spread. It can be caused by an overactive immune system or certain medications. MESH code D017511 is associated with this condition.
Vallecula cancer is a type of oropharynx cancer that occurs in the vallecula, which is a small area at the back of the throat. It can also be referred to as malignant tumor of Vallecula.

Oropharynx cancer is a type of pharyngeal cancer that occurs in the oropharynx, which is the middle part of the throat between the tonsils and the soft palate. It can also be referred to as Oropharyngeal carcinoma or malignant Oropharyngeal tumor. The oropharynx is a common location for cancer due to various risk factors such as smoking, heavy alcohol consumption, exposure to certain viruses like the human papillomavirus (HPV), and poor diet. Early detection and treatment are crucial in reducing the chances of complications and improving the survival rate.

Biotinidase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to metabolize biotin, resulting in symptoms such as seizures, developmental delay, and skin rash. It is caused by mutations in the BTD gene on chromosome 3p25, which can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. The condition has exact synonyms including Juvenile-onset multiple carboxylase deficiency, Late-onset multiple carboxylase deficiency, and deficiency of biotinidase.

text: Lip cancer, also known as oral cavity cancer, is a type of malignant neoplasm that originates in the lip or mouth area. It can occur on the upper or lower lip and may involve the vermilion border, labial commissure, or other sites within the lip region. Lip cancer can be classified as squamous cell carcinoma, which is the most common type, or other types such as verrucous carcinoma, ameloblastic carcinoma, and sarcoma. Early detection and treatment are crucial to ensure a successful outcome for patients with lip cancer.

herpes simplex is a type of viral infectious disease that causes skin to break out in small blisters, commonly found on the face and genitals. It is caused by the human alphaherpesvirus 1 or human alphaherpesvirus 2, which are transmitted through direct contact with an active lesion or body fluid from an infected person. The disease can be located in various parts of the body including the mouth, face, hands, and reproductive structure. It has the material basis in Human herpesvirus 1 or Human herpesvirus 2.<|end|>

Hodgkin's lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system. It is characterized by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells, which are abnormal white blood cells. Hodgkin's lymphoma can occur at any age but is most common in people between the ages of 60 and 70. It is treated with chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of both. The prognosis for Hodgkin's lymphoma depends on the stage of the cancer, but with early detection and appropriate treatment, it can be cured.

Multiple Carboxylase Deficiency (MCD) is a type of inborn error of metabolism that affects carbohydrate metabolism. It occurs due to the deficiency of one or more enzymes involved in glycogen metabolism, which leads to an accumulation of glycogen in the liver and other tissues.
MCD can be diagnosed through newborn screening tests, which detect the absence of one or more carboxylase enzymes. Treatment for MCD is aimed at managing symptoms and preventing complications. This may include a special diet, medication, and monitoring by healthcare professionals. With proper management, individuals with MCD can lead a relatively normal life.

Lichen nitidus, also known as Pinkus' disease, is a specific type of lichen that affects the skin. It presents itself with symptoms such as itching and red, shiny patches on the skin, which can be mistaken for an insect bite or rash. However, it's important to note that these symptoms are caused by a reaction to the fungus responsible for lichen nitidus, rather than an actual bug bite or infestation. The disease is typically harmless and self-limiting, which means that it will eventually go away on its own without any specific treatment. In some cases, it may be necessary to use over-the-counter creams or ointments to help alleviate the itching and inflammation caused by lichen nitidus. However, it's always best to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

ulcerative colitis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the gastrointestinal tract. It is characterized by inflammation and ulcers in the colon, and is often accompanied by an elevated level of abnormal immunoglobulins. The exact cause of ulcerative colitis is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to a combination of environmental and genetic factors. It can be classified as left-sided or right-sided, depending on which portion of the colon is affected.
